for agent execution\n   - `SwarmTool` for parallel agent coordination\n   - `PlanMode` for structured execution\n   - `Task` tool for tracking phase completion\n\n## Implementation\n\n### Contract Between Driver and Navigator\n\n| Phase | Driver Responsibility | Navigator Responsibility | Output\n|-------|-----------------------|--------------------------|--------\n| 1     | —                     | Draft test spec          | Test spec (markdown)\n| 2     | Write failing test     | Review test spec         | Failing test (code + assertion error)\n| 3     | Write minimum code     | —                       | Passing test (code)\n| 4     | —                     | Propose refactor         | Refactor plan (markdown)\n| 5     | Apply refactor         | —                       | Refactored code (code)\n| 6     | —                     | Validate refactor        | Validation result (pass/fail + summary)\n\n### Phase Transitions\n\n- **Phase 1 → 2**: Navigator approves test spec → Driver writes test\n- **Phase 2 → 3**: Test fails → Driver writes implementation\n- **Phase 3 → 4**: Test passes → Navigator proposes refactor\n- **Phase 4 → 5**: Driver applies refactor → Navigator validates\n- **Phase 5 → 6**: Refactor applied → Navigator confirms tests pass\n\n### Error Handling\n\n- If **Phase 2** test passes: Navigator revises spec (back to Phase 1)\n- If **Phase 6** validation fails: Navigator proposes fixes (back to Phase 4 or 5)\n\n### Tooling\n\n- **SwarmTool**: Spawn Driver and Navigator as parallel subagents\n- **TaskTool**: Track phase completion and enforce order\n- **BashTool**: Run tests and capture output\n- **EditTool**: Modify code and test files\n- **ReadTool**: Inspect code and test files\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n1. **Single-Agent TDD**: One agent performs all phases. Rejected because it lacks the collaborative review and separation of concerns that improve quality.\n\n2. **Three-Agent TDD**: Driver, Navigator, and Validator. Rejected as overkill — the Navigator can validate refactors.\n\n3. **External TDD Orchestrator**: Build a separate service. Rejected — violates D.U.H.'s principle of self-contained execution.\n\n4. **Hook-Based TDD**: Use hooks to enforce TDD. Rejected — hooks are for cross-cutting concerns, not structured workflows.\n\n## Consequences\n\n### Positive\n\n- Enforces TDD discipline in AI-assisted coding\n- Improves test coverage and code quality\n- Provides clear separation of concerns between test design and implementation\n- Reuses existing abstractions (PlanMode, SwarmTool, TaskTool)\n- Works with any provider (stub, Anthropic, OpenAI, etc.)\n\n### Negative\n\n- Increases token usage due to multi-agent coordination\n- Slower than single-agent execution due to strict phase ordering\n- Requires careful error handling for phase transitions\n\n### Risks\n\n- **Deadlock**: If Navigator and Driver disagree, the flow could stall. Mitigated by:\n  - Timeouts on each phase\n  - User intervention via `/plan abort` or `/plan skip-phase`\n  - Fallback to single-agent mode\n\n- **Token Bloat**: Multi-agent coordination increases prompt size. Mitigated by:\n  - Aggressive compaction between phases\n  - Limiting phase history to current and previous phase\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\nUnit tests will cover:\n- Phase transitions happen in order\n- RED phase surfaces assertion failure distinctly from GREEN\n- Navigator's refactor suggestion is actually applied before validation\n- Full flow completes end-to-end against a stub provider\n\nIntegration tests will:\n- Run the full TDD flow on a sample Python module\n- Validate test coverage increases\n- Confirm refactors are applied and validated\n\n## Documentation\n\n- **README.md**: New section describing the feature with a short example\n- **Wiki**: New page (`docs/wiki/TDD-Flow.md`) with usage, flags, and a worked example\n- **Help Text**: Update `--help` and `/help` to document the new plan mode and slash command")
